Key Match Events: Ben Stokes scored an unbeaten 84 off 76 balls
Jonny Bairstow and Joe Root hit half-centuries
David Willey took 3 wickets for 56 runs and became the 14th England men's player to reach 100 wickets in the ODI format
Adil Rashid and Moeen Ali took 2 wickets each
Abdullah Shafique was dismissed for a duck off the second ball of the innings
Fakhar Zaman was dismissed for 1 off the fourth ball of the innings
Babar Azam was caught at midwicket for 38 off Gus Atkinson
Mohammad Rizwan was caught for 36 off Moeen Ali
Agha Salman was dismissed for 51 off David Willey
Shaheen Shah Afridi, Mohammad Wasim, and Haris Rauf connected some big late shots but it was too little too late
Pre-Game Insights: Pakistan had slim chances of reaching the semi-finals and needed a massive margin to force a swing on net run rate
England built towards a sizeable first-innings score of 337/9
Ben Stokes' future in the One Day International format is uncertain
England secured a guaranteed top-eight finish that cements the team’s qualification for the next Champions Trophy
Pakistan's openers Abdullah Shafique and Fakhar Zaman were dismissed early in the second innings
Post-Match Reflections: Jos Buttler decided to bat after winning the toss
England's openers flourished in Kolkata despite early hostility from Shaheen Afridi and Haris Rauf
Stokes and Root added 36 runs in overs 36-40
England's innings was at risk of petering out, but Jos Buttler, Harry Brook, Moeen Ali, and David Willey smashed sixes in an excellent display of late hitting
David Willey reached his 100th ODI wicket in his final international game
Miscellaneous Highlights: England secured a 93-run victory over Pakistan
David Willey's spell of swing-bowling early in the second innings saw Pakistan lose both of their openers
On a turning wicket, Adil Rashid and Moeen took advantage of the scoreboard pressure
Pakistan's hopes were effectively snuffed out when Moeen Ali saw Mohammad Rizwan coming, pulled back his length, and turned the ball back through the gate to clean up Pakistan’s number four for 36
